{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643990"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:00:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:00:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18027"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18027"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.06,0.02,0.2,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73309"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10741"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1132"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25066"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73309"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with fatigue and pallor. She has a known history of thalassemia major and receives regular blood transfusions. On examination, she appears pale but is otherwise well. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. A recent skull X-ray was performed as part of her routine follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following skull changes is most likely to be seen on her X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Copper beaten skull","Wormian bones","Sclerotic lesions","Lytic lesions","Hair-on-end appearance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn thalassemia major, chronic anaemia leads to increased erythropoiesis, which causes expansion of the bone marrow. This expansion can result in characteristic changes in the skull, most notably the \u003Cstrong\u003Ehair-on-end appearance\u003C/strong\u003E on X-ray. This appearance is due to the vertical striations of new bone formation as the marrow expands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELytic lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are typically associated with conditions like multiple myeloma or metastatic cancer, not thalassemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerotic lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are areas of increased bone density and are not characteristic of thalassemia. They are more commonly seen in conditions like osteopetrosis or Paget\u0027s disease of bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWormian bones\u003C/strong\u003E are extra bone pieces within a suture in the skull and are associated with conditions like osteogenesis imperfecta, not thalassemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECopper beaten skull\u003C/strong\u003E is a term used to describe the appearance of the skull in cases of increased intracranial pressure, such as craniosynostosis, and is not related to thalassemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thalassemia can cause characteristic skull changes due to bone marrow expansion.","The \u0027hair-on-end\u0027 appearance on skull X-rays is indicative of marrow hyperplasia.","These changes are a result of increased erythropoiesis in response to chronic anaemia."],"references":["Mnapo B, Shields M, Koop K. Hair-on-end. Am J Trop Med Hyg. 2013 Apr;88(4):607. doi: 10.4269/ajtmh.12-0498. PMID: 23553223; PMCID: PMC3617840.","Azam M, Bhatti N. Hair-on-end appearance. Arch Dis Child. 2006 Sep;91(9):735. doi: 10.1136/adc.2006.100032. PMID: 16923859; PMCID: PMC2082904.","Ballikar R, Redkar NN, Patil MA, Pillai R. Hair-on-end appearance in a case of thalassemia intermedia. BMJ Case Rep. 2013 Jan 23;2013:bcr2012008095. doi: 10.1136/bcr-2012-008095. Erratum in: BMJ Case Rep. 2013 Mar 12;2013:bcr2012008095corr1. doi: 10.1136/bcr-2012-008095corr1. Balikar, Riya [corrected to Ballikar, Riya]. PMID: 23349179; PMCID: PMC3604553.","Amadi OP, Patel C, Tangella K, Khaliq W. \u0027Hair-on-end\u0027 sign: an important finding in clinical practice. QJM. 2012 Sep;105(9):905-6. doi: 10.1093/qjmed/hcr151. Epub 2011 Aug 24. PMID: 21865306."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18027"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T11:30:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T11:31:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10741"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73309"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","